name: "A Few Clowns Short of a Circus"
description:
Probably a nicer, more gentle way to characterize an unintelligent person.

You’ll be whip-smart and pretty with this colorful and delicate necklace which features two sterling silver clown charms and a striped hollow glass bead that resembles a circus ball.

name: "Don't Throw the Baby Out With the Bath Water"
description:
Throwing the baby out with the bath water is an expression first recorded in 1512 and used by the German writer, Thomas Murner. He suggests one doesn’t need to reject an entire idea, concept or practice if only part of it is good. The baby, in this sense, represents the good part. The bath water, on the other hand, is usually dirty after the baby is washed and needs to be discarded.


A sterling baby pacifier charm dangles next to an air-filled Lucite ball bead which resembles a perfect bath bubble.

name: "House Guarded by Shotgun 3 days per week. Guess which days."
description: A house charm. A gun charm. You get the picture. Necklace is accented with two blue swarovski crystals.

name: "Some Days You're the Dog, Some Days You're the Hydrant"
description: Sterling silver dog and hydrant charms dangle from a red leather neck cord. A vibrant red swarovski crystal dangles between the charms.

name: "Watercolor Bracelet"
description:
Vincent Van Gogh severed his left ear lobe with a razor blade, walked to a nearby bordello and presented it to a prostitute named Rachel.  He told her to "keep this object carefully", but she fainted when she discovered what was inside the package. Ah, to be a tortured genius!


This lightweight bracelet was made using shiny resin, and a sterling silver clasp. The watercolor painting is by yours truly.

name: "Monkey and Banana"
description:
“The monkey and banana problem” is a famous toy problem in artificial intelligence, particularly in logic programming and planning.
The Formulation of the Problem:
A monkey is in a room. Suspended from the ceiling is a bunch of bananas, beyond the monkey's reach. However, in the room there are also a chair and a stick. The ceiling is just the right height so that a monkey standing on a chair could knock the bananas down with the stick. The monkey knows how to move around, carry other things around, reach for the bananas, and wave a stick in the air. What is the best sequence of actions for the monkey to take to acquire lunch?

A sterling silver monkey hangs next to a banana charm on a thin yellow leather cord. The necklace is accented with two small sparkling yellow crystals.

name: "Saving Face"
description:
The noble ladies and gentlemen of the late 18th century wore excessive makeup in order to impress each other. Since they rarely bathed, the makeup would get thicker and thicker as the days went by. If they sat too close to the fireplace, their makeup might melt. If that happened, a servant would move the screen in front of the fireplace to block the heat, so they wouldn't "lose face.”

A silver face and coin purse hang next to a pink swarovski crystal on a thin pink leather cord.

name: "Rubber Duckie and Bubbles"
description:
The yellow rubber duck has achieved an iconic status in Western pop culture and is often symbolically linked to bathing. A "rubber ducky" in German-speaking countries is generally known as a 'Squeaky Duckling' ("Quietscheentchen"). 


A delicate silver duck charm floats in between two hollow glass bath “bubbles”

name: "Burning the Candle at Both Ends"
description:
When a clerk worked late it was hard to see by candle light. If they didn’t have two candles they would simply turn a single candle on its side and light both ends. This produced twice as much light but burned out in half the time. The phrase came to mean someone who worked very hard and would wear themselves out very quickly.

Chandelier-style candlestick charms hang from opposite ends of a 35” sterling silver chain. The necklace is accented with “Fire-colored” orange swarovski crystals.

name: "Minnesota and Snowflake"
description:
One of the largest and longest lasting blizzards in state history happened between October 31-November 3, 1991. Over 28 inches of snow blanketed the Twin Cities region, and nearly 37 inches fell at Duluth.  Nasty windchill conditions and deep snow drifts closed roads for days. 

Vintage enameled Minnesota charm with sterling silver snowflake underneath. An intricate sterling clasp is flanked by green swarovski crystals.

name: "Elephant and Circus Ball"
description:
Step right up, children of all ages! Come and witness the amazing sights and sounds, the bizarre and unbelievable feats, the glitter and spectacle of the American circus!

Goldtone elephant charm with orange swarovski crystals and a single striped glass bead which resembles a circus ball. 24" long.

name: "Loose Lips Sink Ships"
description:
This phrase was coined as a slogan during WWII as part of the US Office of War Information's attempt to limit the possibility of people inadvertently giving useful information to enemy spies.


An anchor charm dangles in-between vibrant red lips and a clear swarovski drop.

name: "Horse and Horseshoe"
description:
“Don’t shut the barn door after the horse is stolen”

The 35" long gray lace ribbon has stretch to it and can be worn a number of different ways. Tiny swarovski crystals accent a
Galloping horse charm on one end and a horseshoe on the other.

name: "Wet your Whistle"
description:
Many years ago, pub goers had a whistle baked into the handles of their ceramic cups. When they needed a refill they would simply blow the whistle to get the attention of the waiter. Now this is what I call service!


Delicate whistle and cup charm accented with small Swarovski crystals

name: "Dog and Bone"
description:
“The dog that trots about finds the bone”


A sterling silver dog on one end and sterling bone charm on the other. Various shades of blue Swarovski crystals and a sterling ring complete the piece.  24" long.

name: "Bathtub and Bubbles"
description:
At the end of WW1 most bathrooms were fitted with a toilet, sink, and bathtub – mostly clawfoot bathtubs. But even in 1921, only one percent of homes in the United Sates had indoor plumbing.


A Sterling silver claw foot bathtub charm twirls beside a vintage lucite ball bead. The air pockets trapped inside the clear bead resemble perfect bath bubbles.

name: "Water Faucet"
description:
For decades, faucets had two handles - one for hot water, and the other for cold. Over 70 years ago, this design changed. One day in 1937, a man named Al Moen turned the faucet handle to wash his hands but scalded himself since the water came out too hot. This mishap inspired him to design the single-handle faucet.

A sterling silver water faucet charm dangles above pale blue crystal water “drops”

name: "Lightbulb"
description:
How many Irish does it take to switch a lightbulb?
None. They’ll drink in the dark.


This small glass lightbulb charm is filled with tiny sparkling swarovski crystals. Available in vibrant red, light green or royal blue.

name: "Table and Chair"
description:
How many types of chairs are there? Too many! Folding,  ergonomic, recliner, butterfly, beanbag, massage…The earliest Western tables were simple boards supported on trestles erected when needed for eating. 


Table and chair charms hang from opposite ends of a delicate multicolored swarovski crystal chain.

name: "Bunny and Carrot"
description:
"What is REAL?" asked the Rabbit one day, when they were lying side by side near the nursery fender, before Nana came to tidy the room. "Does it mean having things that buzz inside you and a stick-out handle?" 
                                    -From the Velveteen Rabbit


An orange enameled carrot charm dangles next to a hungry little rabbit. Chain is accented with a gold circle and vibrant orange Swarovski crystals. 24” long.

name: "Mannequin Head"
description:
Historically, artists have been known to become obsessed with mannequins. When Alma Mahler jilted him, Oscar Schlemmer, the Bauhaus painter, crafted a doll to take her place beside him in his car when driving in Vienna.

This gal sports a bouffant hairdo and seductive sideways glance. She is inspired by a mannequin displayed in a Paris boutique window. 16” chain

name: "Girl Wednesday"
description: This Gothic pendant necklace pays tribute to the work of Edward Gorey, an American writer and artist noted for his macabre illustrations. Pendant hangs on a 18" black chain and measures 1.5" across.
